</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2AC3655CFFA1244CFFC2F8320DF60957" pageId="8" pageNumber="293" type="breeding">
<paragraph id="626636D7FFA1244CFFC2F8320DF60957" blockId="8.[96,1304,726,2653]" pageId="8" pageNumber="293">
<emphasis id="50ADEAC5FFA1244CFFC2F8320FAF0680" bold="true" box="[97,231,1987,2020]" pageId="8" pageNumber="293">Breeding.</emphasis>
There is no specific information for this species, but female Woolley’s Three-striped Dasyures apparently have four nipples in their pouches (based on one museum specimen and two field captures).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2AC3655CFFA1244CFFC3F7CB0B4109CE" pageId="8" pageNumber="293" type="activity">
<paragraph id="626636D7FFA1244CFFC3F7CB0B4109CE" blockId="8.[96,1304,726,2653]" pageId="8" pageNumber="293">
<emphasis id="50ADEAC5FFA1244CFFC3F7CB0E02093F" bold="true" box="[96,330,2106,2139]" pageId="8" pageNumber="293">Activity patterns.</emphasis>
There is no specific information available for this species, but like its congeners, Woolley’s Three-striped Dasyure is thought to be primarily ground dwelling and diurnal. It has been observed active during daylight hours.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2AC3655CFFA1244CFFC2F7400E7E099C" pageId="8" pageNumber="293" type="biology_ecology">
